AB  - Inference procedures for noncausal autoregressive (AR) models have been well studied and applied in a variety of applications from environmental to financial. For such processes, the observation at time t may depend on both past and future shocks in the system. In this paper, we consider extension of the univariate noncausal AR models to the vector AR (VAR) case. The extension presents several interesting challenges since even a first-order VAR can possess both causal and noncausal components. Assuming a non-Gaussian distribution for the noise, we show how to compute an approximation to the likelihood function. Under suitable conditions, it is shown that the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) of the vector of AR parameters is asymptotically normal. The estimation procedure is illustrated with a simulation study for a VAR(1) process and with two real data examples.
